Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have equated the earthquakes, tsunami, and nuclear disaster in Japan to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The similarity is quite clear: each of these activities generates substantial profits and involves a very low but explosive risk.
Yet, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the manner of preventing their reappearance begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with typically harmless design flaws, caused the interruption of cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
Regarding financial markets, an unexpected collapse of real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivative and repo markets, damaged the ability of major financial institutions to honor their debts.
Although the root risks originate outside the systems – a tsunami for Fukushima, an overinvestment in mortgage loans for financial institutions – design flaws and a lack of luck have made it so that the systems were unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers—each with significant investments in derivatives and/or repos—collapsed, causing a freeze in credit markets for several long weeks.
We now understand fairly well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
One cannot say the same about the risks of derivative products, which have shaken the global economy.
At Fukushima, the teams of workers are bravely trying to stop the radiation leaks.
On the contrary, for derivatives, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating derivative products and similar financial structures, above the same errors that are still active.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of the euro's fluctuation but does not want the risk on the yen, whereas for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first one promises to provide euros on June 1st, and the second one promises to provide yen.
If a currency loses value relative to the other, the loser pays the difference.
Rests are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury bills or mortgage-backed securities, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the next day (hence the term "repo," short for the English verb "repurchase" — ed.).
The problem is that the cash from these short-term deposits constitutes a large part of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which means that even minor financial shocks can significantly affect them.
Some institutions may then lose access to repo financing, as in 2008, and go bankrupt, as Bear Stearns did.
Individually considered, transactions on derivatives or repos are not heavily criticized.
Each separately legitimately transfers the risk to those better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when used excessively by institutions that are critical at the systemic level, they can cause the financial system to collapse due to its design flaws.
Even today, approximately 70% of the liabilities of the major American financial institutions consist of very short-term loans, such as overnight repurchase agreements.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repos from most usual constraints in the event of bankruptcy.
For example, investors who hold derivative contracts or repos with financially weakened financial institutions may seize the company's assets before—and at the expense of—its regular creditors. In doing so, they may decide the company's fate, whereas, with a little more time, the company could have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because derivative and repo investors find themselves at the head of the queue for reimbursement in so many ways, they have fewer incentives to encourage market discipline by closely examining the solvability of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be reimbursed anyway.
Certainly, someone must be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because exemptions for derivative and repo market participants place them in the front line in the event of a failure.
Normally, one would expect that others would therefore have an interest in encouraging greater market discipline.
But the actor that follows in the line is often the American government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (i.e., too important to be allowed to fail). However, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a daily basis.
It is not financially agile; it often confines itself to the regulated market; and when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The U.S. Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major financial overhaul it adopted last summer through the Dodd Frank bill.
But he didn't catch it.
If derivative investors, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit-event derivatives, note) did not enjoy favorable treatment, they would behave differently.
First and above all, they would more often insist that their counterparts be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by extremely low capitalizations when it was essentially American government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it were their own money they were risking.
The public perceives differently the risks of the Fukushima type and the risks associated with derivatives.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are striking, causing a slowdown in the sector that must deal with security concerns.
But the markets for derivatives and repos present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate in the media, and complicated to discuss and resolve for politicians.
During a crisis, these markets attract the public's attention and disdain, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding the type of risks associated with Fukushima, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and built to contain the risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis through the use of passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to design nuclear power plants capable of maintaining cold fuel rods even in the event of a complete loss of electrical power.
On the contrary, few significant progress has been made so far in order to prevent the damage that the priority of derivative products and repos in case of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed, which require end-users (such as oil companies using derivatives to hedge against unexpected changes in oil prices) and others to post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main issue: the weak incentives for market discipline for the major financial institutions.
It seems as if we are reacting to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to fully shift the risk associated with their decisions onto investors in derivatives and repos when they engage in transactions with financial institutions that are systemically important.
Instead, we survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same flawed design.
